<subSubSection id="BDD4D095FFE7887E72EA1523FBD4FBA0" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="F571831EFFE7887E72EA1523FE91FD1B" blockId="3.[140,1108,624,1073]" box="[140,261,624,650]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis id="C7BA5F0CFFE7887E72EA1523FE91FD1B" bold="true" box="[140,261,624,650]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F571831EFFE7887E72EA15C7FBD4FBA0" blockId="3.[140,1108,624,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">
Integument with slightly granulate microsculpture, pubescent, pubescence short and of distinct pattern on pronotum with microsetae forming arcuate lines emerging from midline of the disc outwards (
<figureCitation id="6DF59F9BFFE7887E73331589FE07FD65" box="[341,403,730,756]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[140,174,1643,1665]" captionTargetBox="[214,1032,185,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[202,1046,165,1624]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Diglotta mersa (Haliday) in dorsal view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773907/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Body with large, broadly rounded head and protruding mouthparts forming conically-shaped apical projection, head as large as or larger than pronotum (
<figureCitation id="6DF59F9BFFE7887E72F51473FF5BFCAB" box="[147,207,800,826]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[140,174,1643,1665]" captionTargetBox="[214,1032,185,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[202,1046,165,1624]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Diglotta mersa (Haliday) in dorsal view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773907/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); infraorbital carinae absent; labrum broadly emarginate medially; mandibles slender with rounded blunt apices, prostheca well developed; lacinia and galea of equal length; maxillary palpus with four articles, first and last reduced in size; mentum trapezoidal in shape, anterior margin strongly concave; pronotum strongly narrowed basally (
<figureCitation id="6DF59F9BFFE7887E71E414D9FC28FC35" box="[898,956,906,932]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[140,174,1643,1665]" captionTargetBox="[214,1032,185,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[202,1046,165,1624]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Diglotta mersa (Haliday) in dorsal view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773907/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); elytra shorter than pronotum (
<figureCitation id="6DF59F9BFFE7887E733E14FEFE07FC56" box="[344,403,941,967]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[140,174,1643,1665]" captionTargetBox="[214,1032,185,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[202,1046,165,1624]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Diglotta mersa (Haliday) in dorsal view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773907/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); hind wings usually reduced to short stubs, but micropterous and macropterous forms within the same species are reported (
<bibRefCitation id="915FFEEFFFE7887E70991483FC15FC7B" author="Good JA" box="[767,897,976,1002]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" pagination="73 - 76" refId="ref4358" refString="Good JA (1998) The identification and habitat of micropterous Diglotta mersa (Haliday) and D. sinuaticollis (Mulsant &amp; Rey) (Staphylinidae). Coleopterist 7: 73 - 76." type="journal article" year="1998">Good 1998</bibRefCitation>
); abdomen broadly oval in dorsal outline and widening posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="6DF59F9BFFE7887E70C714A0FD75FB9C" box="[673,737,1011,1037]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[140,174,1643,1665]" captionTargetBox="[214,1032,185,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[202,1046,165,1624]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Diglotta mersa (Haliday) in dorsal view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773907/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="178">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Found in the intertidal zone of beaches (
<bibRefCitation id="915FFEEFFFE7887E728D1344FE76FBA0" author="Moore I &amp; Orth RE" box="[235,482,1046,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" pagination="337 - 340" refId="ref4756" refString="Moore I, Orth RE (1979) Diglotta legneri, a new seashore beetle from California (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Th e Coleopterists Bulletin 33: 337 - 340." type="journal article" year="1979">Moore and Orth 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="915FFEEFFFE7887E73881345FDF9FBA0" author="Good JA" box="[494,621,1046,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" pagination="73 - 76" refId="ref4358" refString="Good JA (1998) The identification and habitat of micropterous Diglotta mersa (Haliday) and D. sinuaticollis (Mulsant &amp; Rey) (Staphylinidae). Coleopterist 7: 73 - 76." type="journal article" year="1998">Good 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="915FFEEFFFE7887E701E1345FCA3FBA0" author="Haghebaert G" box="[632,823,1046,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" pagination="223 - 234" refId="ref4436" refString="Haghebaert G (1991) A review of the Diglotta of the world (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae). Bulletin et Annales de la Societe Royale Belge d'Entomologie 127: 223 - 234." type="journal article" year="1991">Haghebaert 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="915FFEEFFFE7887E71241344FC26FBA0" author="Pace R" box="[834,946,1047,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" pagination="180 - 186" refId="ref4909" refString="Pace R (1989) [1992]. Aleocharinae di Gibuti (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae) (XCII Contributo alla conscenza delle Aleocharinae). Bolletino del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Verona 16: 180 - 186." type="journal article" year="1989">Pace 1989</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="915FFEEFFFE7887E71D81345FBA1FBA0" author="Ashe JS" box="[958,1077,1046,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="178" pagination="271 - 418" refId="ref4043" refString="Ashe JS (2001) Keys to the tribes and genera of Nearctic Aleocharinae. In: Arnett RH, Thomas MC (Eds) American Beetles, 1. Archostemata, Myxophaga, Adepahaga, Polyphaga: Staphyliniformia. CRC Press, Boca Raton, Florida, 271 - 418 pp." type="book chapter" year="2001">Ashe 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
